  "prompt": "How do I get out of jury duty?",
  "response": "If you want to be excused from jury duty, you typically need to provide a valid reason. Here are some common steps you can take to request to be excused:\n\n1. **Review the Juror Instructions**: When you receive your jury duty summons, it usually comes with information about how to respond or request an exemption. Read this carefully for specific guidelines.\n\n2. **Check Eligibility Criteria**: Some jurisdictions allow exemptions for certain reasons such as medical issues, financial hardships, caregiving responsibilities, full-time student status, or previous service.\n\n3. **Prepare Documentation**: If you have a valid reason, gather any necessary documentation (e.g., medical records, proof of caregiving responsibilities) to support your request.\n\n4. **Contact the Court**: Reach out to the court listed on your summons to explain your situation. This might involve filling out a form or writing a letter. Be sure to do this promptly, as there may be deadlines.\n\n5. **Follow Up**: If you do not receive a response in a timely manner, follow up to ensure your request has been processed.\n\n6. **Consider Deferral**: If you cannot completely avoid jury duty, some courts allow you to defer your service to a later date.\n\nRemember that not appearing for jury duty without a valid excuse can result in penalties, so it's important to officially request an exemption if you believe you have a valid reason.",
